They have not yet announced the schedule for scrubbing the mission, or for the explosion or collision, but I expect the first some time tomorrow mid-afternoon; or the explosion somewhere between T+5:00 and T+10:00; or the collision, which will probably only be embarrassing and not catastrophic, some time Friday evening. The boeing starliner spacecraft, while it is advertised to be the flagship of the Boeing "SpaceForce", or whatever they wish to call it, has a massive amount of issues following it's creation and flight. Constant valve issues among software issues and... (the list goes on) have kept it grounded for long periods of time, and I believe it would be wise of Boeing to halt the launch temporarily while they seriously reconsider their design of the spacecraft. Will they launch it again? Most definitely Boeing will try, but will it successfully dock with the ISS? I doubt it.

The intended service module (SM) had a valve leak of unknown origin, forcing Boeing to swap SMs. Once swapped, they still need to conduct SM acceptance testing, final wire harness mating, installation of solar array panels, and final closeouts. Then comes SM mating with the crew module and all other regular launch prep. Boeing sounds optimistic about making the May launch window, but I think it may prove too much to do by then, and too much to meet the closing of this question on June 15. Boeing's updates are at https://starlinerupdates.com

Seems a very specific and solvable issue caused the first attempt to fail. For reputational reasons, if nothing else, the engineers as Boeing will have a high degree of confidence that the launch is on-track.
